{"title_page": "Home Media Magazine", "text_new": "{{Infobox magazine\n|name=Home Media Magazine\n|company =Questex Media Group\n|country=[[United States]]\n|language=English\n|founded=July 1979<ref>{{cite book|author=Daniel Herbert|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lV98AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA31&dq=Video+Store++Magazine#v=onepage&q=Video%20Store%20%20Magazine&f=false|title=Videoland: Movie Culture at the American Video Store|page=31|accessdate=October 8, 2019|isbn = 9780520958029|date = 2014-01-24}}</ref>\n|based   = Santa Ana, California\n|frequency=Monthly}}\n\n'''''Home Media Magazine''''' was a trade publication that covered various aspects of the [[entertainment industry|home entertainment industry]], most notably home video distribution via VHS, DVD, [[Blu-ray]], and digital copy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.homemediamagazine.com/about-us/about-us|title=About us|work=Home Media Magazine|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> The magazine also covered news relating to consumer electronics, video games, home video distributors and various forms of digital distribution of movie and TV content.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.brighthub.com/electronics/home-theater/articles/62370.aspx|title=Top 4 Home Theater Magazines|work=Bright Hub|date=January 10, 2010|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> Staff included  Bruce Apar, reporter Enrique Rivero(who previously worked at Los Angeles Daily News),John Gaudiosi among others.<ref name=\"Hive\">{{cite web|first=Don|last=Rosenberg|url=http://www.hive4media.com/news/html/Industry_Article.cfm?article_id=1392|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010715125431/http://www.hive4media.com/news/html/Industry_Article.cfm?article_id=1392|title=Video Store Magazine Announces Its All-Star Lineup By Don Rorsenberg|website=[[Hive4media.com]]|archivedate=July 15, 2001|date=June 29, 2001|accessdate=September 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History and profile==\nThe magazine was founded in 1979 and was known as ''Video Store Magazine'' until 2005,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20050113005500/en/Home-Media-Retailing-Video-Store-Magazine|title=Home Media Retailing: A New Name and Look for Video Store Magazine|work=Business News|date=January 15, 2005|accessdate=October 1, 2013}}</ref> when it became ''Home Media Retailing''. The name change was first announced in October 2004.<ref>{{cite web|first=Don|last=Rosenberg|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/14891203/new-name-new-era-entertainment-retailing|title=A New Name for a New Era in Entertainment Retailing|magazine=Video Store Magazine|page=6|date=October 24, 2004|accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref> To further its consumer focus, the magazine dropped \"Retailing\" at the beginning of 2007. In 2014 the magazine's print edition was reduced to biweekly and in 2015, to monthly; at the same time, the publication increased its web presence through a daily e-newsletter and frequent \"breaking news\" alerts. ''HM'' also published frequent special issues, such as special reports on 4K Ultra HD, Vidity, and UltraViolet; rankings of the top women in home entertainment, key digital drivers, and leading disruptors; and, in 2011, a salute to executives in home entertainment under the age of 40.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110914005477/en/Home-Media-Magazine-Presents-%E2%80%9CForty-Forty%E2%80%9D|title=Home Media Magazine Presents 'Forty Under Forty'|work=BusinessWire|date=September 14, 2011|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe magazine was based in Santa Ana, California, and was a subsidiary of the Questex Media Group.\n\nIn July 2006, ''HM'' launched a consumer magazine called ''Agent DVD'', a semi-regular periodical focusing on home entertainment news. The first issue debuted at the 2006 [[Comic Con International]] in San Diego, California, and focused on titles and news that would appeal to convention-goers. The consumer magazine was later rebranded as ''Home Media Insider'' and offered only in digital form.\n\nAdditionally, ''Home Media Magazine'' presented annual awards covering the best DVD and Blu-ray products.\n\nQuestex ceased production of ''Home Media Magazine'' after the December 2017 issue.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bluetoad.com/publication/?i=462137&ver=html5&p=3|title=What a Long, Strange Trip|work=Home Media Magazine|date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> At the beginning of 2018, the core team responsible for producing the ''Home Media Magazine'' print and online properties returned with an independent operation called ''Media Play News'' that offers an expanded home entertainment focus from its predecessor, covering not just Blu-ray Disc and DVD but also transactional video-on-demand (both streaming and purchase) as well as subscription streaming. The new publication publishes a monthly magazine in both print and digital versions and maintains a website, a daily newsletter and breaking news alerts.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.mediaplaynews.com/redefining-home-entertainment/|title=Redefining Home Entertainment \u2013 Welcome to Media Play News!|work=Media Play News|date=January 2, 2018|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mediaplaynews.com ''Media Play News'' Website]\n\n[[Category:American weekly magazines]]\n[[Category:American entertainment magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1979]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in California]]\n[[Category:Media in Orange County, California]]\n[[Category:Professional and trade magazines]]\n[[Category:American science and technology magazines]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox magazine\n|name=Home Media Magazine\n|company =Questex Media Group\n|country=[[United States]]\n|language=English\n|founded=July 1979<ref>{{cite book|author=Daniel Herbert|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lV98AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA31&dq=Video+Store++Magazine#v=onepage&q=Video%20Store%20%20Magazine&f=false|title=Videoland: Movie Culture at the American Video Store|page=31|accessdate=October 8, 2019|isbn = 9780520958029|date = 2014-01-24}}</ref>\n|based   = Santa Ana, California\n|frequency=Monthly}}\n\n'''''Home Media Magazine''''' was a trade publication that covered various aspects of the [[entertainment industry|home entertainment industry]], most notably home video distribution via VHS, DVD, [[Blu-ray]], and digital copy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.homemediamagazine.com/about-us/about-us|title=About us|work=Home Media Magazine|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> The magazine also covered news relating to consumer electronics, video games, home video distributors and various forms of digital distribution of movie and TV content.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.brighthub.com/electronics/home-theater/articles/62370.aspx|title=Top 4 Home Theater Magazines|work=Bright Hub|date=January 10, 2010|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> Staff included  Bruce Apar, reporter Enrique Rivero(who previously worked at Los Angeles Daily News),John Gaudiosi among others.<ref name=\"Hive\">{{cite web|first=Don|last=Rosenberg|url=http://www.hive4media.com/news/html/Industry_Article.cfm?article_id=1392|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010715125431/http://www.hive4media.com/news/html/Industry_Article.cfm?article_id=1392|title=Video Store Magazine Announces Its All-Star Lineup By Don Rorsenberg|website=[[Hive4media.com]]|archivedate=July 15, 2001|date=June 29, 2001|accessdate=September 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History and profile==\nThe magazine was founded in 1979 and was known as ''Video Store Magazine'' until 2005,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20050113005500/en/Home-Media-Retailing-Video-Store-Magazine|title=Home Media Retailing: A New Name and Look for Video Store Magazine|work=Business News|date=January 15, 2005|accessdate=October 1, 2013}}</ref> when it became ''Home Media Retailing''. The name change was first announced in October 2004.<ref>{{cite web|first=Don|last=Rosenberg|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/14891203/new-name-new-era-entertainment-retailing|title=A New Name for a New Era in Entertainment Retailing|magazine=Video Store Magazine|page=6|date=October 24, 2004|accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref> To further its consumer focus, the magazine dropped \"Retailing\" at the beginning of 2007. In 2014 the magazine's print edition was reduced to biweekly and in 2015, to monthly; at the same time, the publication increased its web presence through a daily e-newsletter and frequent \"breaking news\" alerts. ''HM'' also published frequent special issues, such as special reports on 4K Ultra HD, Vidity, and UltraViolet; rankings of the top women in home entertainment, key digital drivers, and leading disruptors; and, in 2011, a salute to executives in home entertainment under the age of 40.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110914005477/en/Home-Media-Magazine-Presents-%E2%80%9CForty-Forty%E2%80%9D|title=Home Media Magazine Presents 'Forty Under Forty'|work=BusinessWire|date=September 14, 2011|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe magazine was based in Santa Ana, California, and was a subsidiary of the Questex Media Group.\n\nIn July 2006, ''HM'' launched a consumer magazine called ''Agent DVD'', a semi-regular periodical focusing on home entertainment news. The first issue debuted at the 2006 [[Comic Con International]] in San Diego, California, and focused on titles and news that would appeal to convention-goers. The consumer magazine was later rebranded as ''Home Media Insider'' and offered only in digital form.\n\nAdditionally, ''Home Media Magazine'' presented annual awards covering the best DVD and Blu-ray products.\n\nQuestex ceased production of ''Home Media Magazine'' after the December 2017 issue.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bluetoad.com/publication/?i=462137&ver=html5&p=3|title=What a Long, Strange Trip|work=Home Media Magazine|date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> At the beginning of 2018, the core team responsible for producing the ''Home Media Magazine'' print and online properties returned with an independent operation called ''Media Play News'' that offers an expanded home entertainment focus from its predecessor, covering not just Blu-ray Disc and DVD but also transactional video-on-demand (both streaming and purchase) as well as subscription streaming. The new publication publishes a monthly magazine in both print and digital versions and maintains a website, a daily newsletter and breaking news alerts.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.mediaplaynews.com/redefining-home-entertainment/|title=Redefining Home Entertainment \u2013 Welcome to Media Play News!|work=Media Play News|date=January 2, 2018|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://homemediamagazine.com ''Home Media Magazine'' Website]\n* [http://mediaplaynews.com ''Media Play News'' Website]\n\n[[Category:American weekly magazines]]\n[[Category:American entertainment magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1979]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in California]]\n[[Category:Media in Orange County, California]]\n[[Category:Professional and trade magazines]]\n[[Category:American science and technology magazines]]\n", "name_user": "Tkarnold", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:link no longer directs to defunct magazine", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home_Media_Magazine"}
